
[1]sarcophagus

   SARCOPH'AGUS, n. [L. from Gr. flesh and to eat.]

   1. A species of stone used among the Greeks in their sculptures, which
   was so called because it consumed the flesh of bodies deposited in it
   within a few weeks. It is otherwise called lapis Assius, and said to be
   found at Assos, a city of Lycia Hence,

   2. A stone coffin or grave in which the ancients deposited bodies which
   they chose not to burn.
